// Heritage Philippines V3 — Prisma schema.
//
// Phase 1 scope so far: the shared identity model (User) and the six
// blueprint-approved roles (blueprint Section 4); the Session/Account/
// Verification models Better Auth's Prisma adapter requires for
// database-backed authentication (docs/HERITAGE_V3_DECISIONS_LOG.md D-011);
// StaffProfile and AuditLog, as Checkpoint 1 (schema only) of the "staff
// account, role, and assignment management" checklist item
// (docs/HERITAGE_V3_DECISIONS_LOG.md D-012); Lead, LeadStatusHistory,
// Client, and StaffAssignment, as Checkpoint 1 (schema only) of the
// "database schema implementation" checklist item (blueprint Sections 4, 5,
// 6, 13.2, 13.3, 14.1, 14.2); ClientProfile and PortalInvitation, as
// Checkpoint 1 (schema only) of the Client Portal Ownership Foundation
// (blueprint Sections 4.6, 5, 7, 14.1, 14.2); and Proposal, ProposalVersion,
// and ProposalAcceptance, as Checkpoint 1 (schema only) of the Proposal /
// ROS Schema Foundation (blueprint Sections 5, 8, 9, 9.1, 14.4).
//
// The Lead/LeadStatusHistory/Client/StaffAssignment models are covered by
// migration `20260714024613_lead_client_assignment_foundation`, which
// includes the two hand-added PostgreSQL constraints Prisma's schema
// language cannot express on its own (the StaffAssignment
// leadId/clientId XOR CHECK constraint and its two partial unique
// indexes — see the StaffAssignment model doc comment below, which states
// both requirements and their raw SQL directly). This migration's presence
// in this repository does not by itself confirm it has been applied to
// every environment (local, staging, production) — see
// docs/HERITAGE_V3_TASK_BOARD.md for the current, up-to-date status of
// which environments have actually run it.
//
// ClientProfile and PortalInvitation are covered by migration
// `20260715014939_client_portal_ownership_foundation`. This migration's
// presence in this repository does not by itself confirm it has been
// applied to every environment (local, staging, production) — see
// docs/HERITAGE_V3_TASK_BOARD.md for the current, up-to-date status. No
// invitation/activation service, raw token generation/hashing
// implementation, email delivery, account-creation code, API route, or
// client portal UI exists anywhere in this repository yet — see the
// ClientProfile and PortalInvitation model doc comments below for exactly
// what each still defers. The `canAccessClient` client-portal-ownership
// authorization check that reads ClientProfile (blueprint Sections 4.6,
// 14.1) is implemented in apps/web/src/features/assignments/authorization.ts
// as of the Client Portal Ownership Enforcement checkpoint, but is not yet
// wired into any client-facing route, since no such route exists yet.
//
// Proposal, ProposalVersion, and ProposalAcceptance are covered by
// create-only migration `20260715055859_proposal_ros_foundation`, which
// contains the two hand-written PostgreSQL statements Prisma's schema
// language cannot express on its own — a partial unique index enforcing
// at most one current client-visible ProposalVersion per Proposal, and a
// CHECK constraint enforcing a complete, mutually exclusive
// portal/external response-attribution path on ProposalAcceptance; see
// the ProposalVersion and ProposalAcceptance model doc comments below for
// both statements verbatim. This file does not claim that migration has
// been applied to any environment (local, staging, or production) —
// docs/HERITAGE_V3_TASK_BOARD.md remains the source for verified
// environment/migration-application status. No proposal content
// (itinerary, quotation, pricing, currency), repository layer, service
// layer, API routes, client portal or admin dashboard UI, tests, or seed
// data exist anywhere in this repository yet for this checkpoint — see
// each model's own doc comment for exactly what is, and is not, covered.
//
// Booking, BookingStatusHistory, and the StaffAssignment extension making
// Booking a supported assignment target are covered by this checkpoint —
// the Booking Schema Foundation schema-and-migration checkpoint (blueprint
// Sections 5, 5.1, 5.2, 8, 9, 13.4, 14.1, 14.5; .claude/rules/backend.md
// Auditability; .claude/rules/database-security.md Identifiers and
// Timestamps). Migration `20260716020734_booking_schema_foundation`
// contains this checkpoint's schema operations and PostgreSQL constraints,
// including replacing the prior two-target StaffAssignment lead/client XOR
// constraint with a three-target lead/client/booking XOR constraint,
// adding the booking active-assignment partial unique index, and adding
// the Booking and BookingStatusHistory CHECK constraints (see the Booking,
// BookingStatusHistory, and StaffAssignment model doc comments below for
// each). This migration's presence in this repository does not by itself
// confirm it has been applied to any environment (local, staging, or
// production) — docs/HERITAGE_V3_TASK_BOARD.md remains the source for
// verified environment/migration-application status. This checkpoint
// deliberately does not model TourPackage as a catalogue entity or
// relation (only an optional `tourPackageName` point-in-time snapshot
// string), ItineraryVersion or any structured itinerary content, Booking
// total price or currency (blocked on the unresolved currency strategy,
// docs/HERITAGE_V3_DECISIONS_LOG.md D-002), or structured per-traveller
// records (only an optional `travelerCount` scalar) — see the Booking
// model doc comment for each. Services, APIs, UI, tests, and seed data for
// Booking all remain deferred to future checkpoints.
//
// Conversation, ConversationParticipant, Message, and MessageAttachment are
// covered by this checkpoint — the Conversation Schema Foundation
// schema-and-migration checkpoint (blueprint Sections 4.2-4.6, 9.1, 10,
// 10.1, 10.2, 10.3, 13.9, 14.3; docs/HERITAGE_V3_DECISIONS_LOG.md D-016).
// This checkpoint spans two migrations rather than one, because of an
// implementation-session incident recorded in D-016: migration
// `20260717010445_conversation_schema_foundation` contains the four new
// tables, three new enums, and their standard (non-partial, non-CHECK)
// indexes and foreign keys — it was applied to the local `heritage_v3_dev`
// database ahead of schedule, before its accompanying hand-written
// PostgreSQL constraints existed, and was left byte-for-byte unchanged
// rather than edited post-application (editing an already-applied
// migration file would desync its checksum from the recorded
// `_prisma_migrations` row). Migration
// `20260717010520_conversation_schema_constraints` — created empty by the
// same incident, then renamed and populated with every hand-written
// PostgreSQL constraint and partial unique index Prisma's schema language
// cannot express on its own (see the Conversation, ConversationParticipant,
// and Message model doc comments below for each constraint and its
// rationale) — was reviewed and then also applied. Both migrations were
// successfully applied to local `heritage_v3_dev` on July 17, 2026;
// `prisma migrate status` subsequently reported all 8 migrations applied
// and the schema up to date (D-016). Their application to staging or
// production is not implied by this file and must be verified
// independently — docs/HERITAGE_V3_TASK_BOARD.md remains the source for
// verified environment/migration-application status. This checkpoint
// deliberately modeled at most one related record per Conversation (an
// optional Booking or an optional Proposal, never both) and deferred a
// VisaCase relation entirely, since VisaCase did not exist anywhere in
// this schema at the time. The Visa Case Schema Foundation checkpoint,
// Stage A (docs/HERITAGE_V3_DECISIONS_LOG.md D-017) has since added
// `Conversation.relatedVisaCaseId` at the schema level — see the
// Conversation model's own doc comment below for its current, up-to-date
// state and the still-pending three-column constraint replacement.
// Read state is modeled as a per-participant
// `ConversationParticipant.lastReadAt` timestamp (D-016), not a shared
// Message-level boolean, since a Conversation may have more than two
// participants. No Conversation status/lifecycle field, subject/title
// field, or `lastMessageAt` denormalization exists — none is defined
// anywhere in blueprint Section 10, so none is invented here. See the file
// header's "Deliberately out of scope here" list below, and each model's
// own doc comment, for the full list of what this checkpoint still defers
// (repository/service layers, API routes, UI, authorization, email
// notification delivery, attachment malware scanning/signed-URL issuance,
// and tests/seed data).
//
// VisaCase and VisaStatusHistory, and the StaffAssignment/Conversation
// extensions making VisaCase a supported assignment target and Conversation
// related-record type, are covered by this checkpoint — the Visa Case
// Schema Foundation checkpoint (blueprint Sections 4.5, 4.7, 5, 5.1, 5.2, 8,
// 13.8, 14.1, 14.8; docs/HERITAGE_V3_DECISIONS_LOG.md D-017). Stage A first
// added this schema and D-017 without creating or applying any migration.
// Migration `20260717024618_visa_case_schema_foundation` was subsequently
// generated, reviewed, hand-augmented with the constraints D-017 requires
// (see the StaffAssignment and Conversation model doc comments below for
// each), and applied to the local `heritage_v3_dev` database on July 17,
// 2026 — `docs/HERITAGE_V3_TASK_BOARD.md` records this. It has not been
// applied to staging or production, and service/API enforcement and every
// other deferred item listed below remain deferred regardless.
// Per D-017: this checkpoint models exactly one VisaCase per Booking for
// the MVP (`VisaCase.bookingId @unique`) — not multiple historical or
// simultaneous VisaCases, and not traveler-level VisaCase modeling, both
// out of scope. `VisaCaseStatus` is a full nine-value enum this checkpoint
// itself defines (D-017), unlike every earlier status enum in this file:
// blueprint Section 13.8 explicitly states "the detailed visa status list
// will be finalized alongside implementation planning" and Section 16.2
// separately lists it as an open decision — D-017 resolves it, so this is
// the one enum in this file whose values come from an explicit decision
// rather than being adopted directly from blueprint text. No transition
// matrix is modeled or implied by the enum's ordering; that is explicitly
// deferred to a later service/API checkpoint, matching how BookingStatus's
// transition matrix was deferred to its own later D-014 checkpoint.
//
// Deliberately out of scope for this checkpoint (Stage A and beyond):
// - VisaRequirement, Document, DocumentRequirement, and DocumentReview —
//   VisaRequirement's blueprint description (Section 14.8) overlaps
//   structurally with DocumentRequirement (Section 14.7), and neither
//   Document nor DocumentRequirement exists anywhere in this schema yet;
//   modeling VisaRequirement now risks a shape that would need reworking
//   once those entities land. No placeholder document model is added.
// - Any applicant/traveler, passport, nationality, embassy, or other
//   identity-document field — VisaCase in this checkpoint is a workflow/
//   status shell only, consistent with the data-minimization principle in
//   `.claude/rules/database-security.md` and blueprint Section 9.1's
//   caution against storing identity documents or unrelated personal
//   information outside their proper, dedicated model.
// - Any notes or arbitrary JSON field on VisaCase — blueprint Section 13.8
//   gives no VisaCase field list (unlike Client Section 13.3 or Booking
//   Section 13.4), so none is invented.
// - `features/assignments`' `TargetKind` union, service, audit, and
//   authorization code — VisaCase is added as a schema-level
//   StaffAssignment target only (see the StaffAssignment model doc
//   comment below); wiring it into the assignment service is a separate,
//   later checkpoint, exactly mirroring how the Booking Schema Foundation
//   checkpoint added `bookingId` to the schema without touching
//   `features/assignments`, with that wiring following in the later,
//   separate D-015 checkpoint.
// - VisaCase/VisaStatusHistory repository and service layers, API routes,
//   admin dashboard and client portal UI, VisaCase-authorization rules
//   (who may create or change a VisaCase; how VisaCase-level and
//   Booking-level StaffAssignment interact — both left open by D-017, not
//   assumed here), status-transition enforcement, notifications, and
//   tests/seed data — all deferred to future checkpoints.
//
// Deliberately out of scope here:
// - A Client status field/enum — the blueprint does not define an approved
//   status list for it anywhere; see the Client model doc comment.
// - A Permission database table — permissions stay expressed in code
//   (src/lib/auth/roles.ts) for Phase 1, not modeled as data; see D-012.
// - Better Auth admin-plugin fields (banned/banReason/banExpires/
//   impersonatedBy) — the plugin was evaluated and rejected; see D-012.
// - Portal invitation preparation, sending, resending, opening, revoking,
//   expiration processing, and account activation as *services*; raw
//   invitation-token generation/hashing; email delivery; client-facing API
//   routes; and client portal UI — all deferred to future checkpoints.
//   Public self-service signup remains explicitly out of scope (blueprint
//   Section 7).
// - An invitation-expiration duration — blueprint Section 16.2 leaves this
//   an open decision; only `PortalInvitation.expiresAt` (a plain timestamp
//   field, no default duration) is modeled here.
// - Proposal content: itinerary, quotation/line-item, pricing, and
//   currency fields — their exact shape is not yet approved (the currency
//   strategy, blueprint Section 16.2/D-002, remains unresolved), so none
//   of it is modeled on ProposalVersion in this checkpoint; a later
//   checkpoint adds these fields once their shape is approved, without
//   bypassing D-002.
// - The Proposal/ProposalVersion/ProposalAcceptance repository and service
//   layers; proposal-related API routes; client portal and admin dashboard
//   UI for proposals; tests; and seed data — all deferred to future
//   checkpoints.
// - TourPackage as a catalogue entity/relation, ItineraryVersion and
//   structured itinerary content, Booking total price and currency
//   (blocked on D-002), and structured per-traveller records — all
//   deferred; see the Booking model doc comment below for each.
// - Booking-creation behavior (the service action that turns an accepted
//   ProposalVersion into a Booking); the Booking/BookingStatusHistory
//   repository and service layers; booking-related API routes; client
//   portal and admin dashboard UI for bookings; tests; and seed data — all
//   deferred to future checkpoints.
// - VisaCase as a Conversation related-record type — deferred until that
//   entity exists, matching its existing StaffAssignment deferral above;
//   see the Conversation model doc comment below for the exclusivity
//   constraint a future checkpoint must extend to a three-way check.
// - The Conversation/ConversationParticipant/Message/MessageAttachment
//   repository and service layers; conversation-related API routes; admin
//   dashboard and client portal UI for Support & Messages; conversation
//   and message authorization — including Admin/Manager's full,
//   unconditional visibility (Section 10.1), client ownership and
//   explicit client participation, Travel Consultant active-assignment
//   access, explicit Finance/Visa Documentation participation, and
//   server-side exclusion of INTERNAL_NOTE messages from every
//   client-facing query (D-016; .claude/rules/admin-dashboard.md
//   Visibility Scoping) — the cross-table client-consistency checks noted
//   on the Conversation model doc comment below; Section 10.3's email
//   notification delivery; attachment malware scanning and
//   signed/expiring download-link issuance (Section 12.3); and tests/seed
//   data — all deferred to future checkpoints.
// - Every other later-phase business entity in blueprint Section 14
//   (PaymentPlan, Document, VisaRequirement, etc.) — remaining for later
//   Phase 1 database-schema checkpoints under the "Implement database
//   schema and reviewed migrations from the approved Phase 0 entity plan"
//   checklist item (docs/HERITAGE_V3_TASK_BOARD.md), to support Phase 2+
//   feature implementation once modeled.
//
// learn more about it in the docs: https://pris.ly/d/prisma-schema

generator client {
  provider = "prisma-client"
  output   = "../src/generated/prisma"
}

datasource db {
  provider = "postgresql"
}

// The six roles approved in blueprint Section 4. A User has exactly one Role.
enum Role {
  SYSTEM_ADMINISTRATOR
  ADMIN_MANAGER
  TRAVEL_CONSULTANT
  FINANCE_ACCOUNTING
  VISA_DOCUMENTATION
  CLIENT
}

// --- Invariants for the staff-management service (later checkpoints) ---
// Not implemented by this schema-only checkpoint; recorded here so they are
// not lost before the service checkpoint builds on this schema. See D-012.
// 1. Demoting or deactivating the last active SYSTEM_ADMINISTRATOR must be
//    prevented; checking "is this the last one" and applying the change
//    must run inside a serializable transaction with retry handling, so a
//    concurrent request cannot race past the check.
// 2. A role change or deactivation must revoke the affected user's
//    sessions atomically with the mutation — the same transaction, never a
//    follow-up step that could fail independently.
// 3. Staff-management endpoints accept STAFF_ROLES only (roles.ts) — CLIENT
//    is never a valid value for a staff account's role.
// 4. Credential creation must never log or write a plaintext password to
//    AuditLog or anywhere else — only the hashed credential (already how
//    Better Auth's own `hashPassword` works) is ever persisted.

// The shared identity model for staff and clients (blueprint Section 14.1).
// Better Auth owns id/name/email/emailVerified/image/createdAt/updatedAt;
// `role` is our own additional field (see src/lib/auth/auth.ts), and is
// never settable through the public sign-up API (input: false there) —
// only a direct, trusted, server-side write (e.g. the seed script, or a
// future authorized staff-management feature) may change it.
model User {
  id            String   @id
  name          String
  email         String   @unique
  emailVerified Boolean  @default(false)
  image         String?
  role          Role     @default(CLIENT)
  // Staff deactivation switch (blueprint Section 4.1's "deactivate platform
  // user accounts"). See the invariants block above this model — changing
  // this field is SYSTEM_ADMINISTRATOR-only, must reject self-action, and
  // must never be set by anything other than the future staff-management
  // service.
  isActive      Boolean  @default(true)
  createdAt     DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt     DateTime @updatedAt

  sessions     Session[]
  accounts     Account[]
  staffProfile StaffProfile?
  auditLogs    AuditLog[]

  // Checkpoint 1 of the Lead/Client/StaffAssignment foundation (blueprint
  // Sections 6, 14.1, 14.2). Each relation is explicitly named because
  // StaffAssignment alone has two independent relations to User
  // (assignee vs. assigner); see the LeadStatusHistory and StaffAssignment
  // model doc comments below for the onDelete: Restrict rationale.
  leadStatusChanges       LeadStatusHistory[] @relation("LeadStatusHistoryActor")
  staffAssignmentsHeld    StaffAssignment[]   @relation("StaffAssignmentAssignee")
  staffAssignmentsGranted StaffAssignment[]   @relation("StaffAssignmentAssigner")

  // Checkpoint 1 of the Client Portal Ownership Foundation (blueprint
  // Sections 4.6, 5, 7, 14.1). Present only for a CLIENT-role User whose
  // portal account has been activated — see the ClientProfile model doc
  // comment for why this schema cannot itself enforce that role invariant.
  clientProfile ClientProfile?

  // Checkpoint 1 of the Proposal / ROS Schema Foundation (blueprint
  // Sections 5, 9, 9.1, 14.4). `proposalVersionsAuthored`: every
  // ProposalVersion this staff member drafted. `recordedProposalResponses`:
  // every externally recorded client response (Section 9.1) this staff
  // member entered — never populated for portal responses, which are
  // attributed to a ClientProfile instead (see ProposalAcceptance below).
  proposalVersionsAuthored  ProposalVersion[]
  recordedProposalResponses ProposalAcceptance[]

  // The Booking Schema Foundation schema-and-migration checkpoint
  // (blueprint Sections 5, 13.4, 14.5). Booking creation is an explicit
  // staff action (blueprint Section 5.1). Booking status changes require
  // actor/timestamp auditability (.claude/rules/backend.md Auditability).
  // Making this User relation required (not nullable) is the approved
  // schema policy for this checkpoint; see the BookingStatusHistory model
  // doc comment below.
  bookingStatusChanges BookingStatusHistory[] @relation("BookingStatusHistoryActor")

  // The Conversation Schema Foundation schema-and-migration checkpoint
  // (blueprint Sections 10, 10.1, 14.3). `conversationParticipations`:
  // every Conversation this staff member currently or formerly
  // participated in (TRAVEL_CONSULTANT, FINANCE_ACCOUNTING, or
  // VISA_DOCUMENTATION capacity — see ConversationParticipant's own doc
  // comment for the role/identity split). `authoredMessages`: every
  // Message this staff member sent — never populated for a client-authored
  // Message, which is attributed to a ClientProfile instead (see the
  // Message model doc comment below).
  conversationParticipations ConversationParticipant[]
  authoredMessages           Message[]

  // The Visa Case Schema Foundation checkpoint, Stage A (blueprint
  // Sections 4.5, 14.8; docs/HERITAGE_V3_DECISIONS_LOG.md D-017). Every
  // VisaStatusHistory row this staff member wrote — required on every row,
  // including the initial one, per D-017's own MVP policy, not something
  // blueprint Section 5.1 itself imposes: Section 5.1 establishes only
  // that a VisaCase is created deliberately, by an explicit staff *or
  // system* action, never automatically as a side effect — it does not by
  // itself require every creation or status change to be
  // staff-attributed. Matches `BookingStatusHistory.changedByUserId`'s
  // required shape, unlike `LeadStatusHistory.changedByUserId`'s nullable
  // one. A future automated or actorless status-change path would require
  // a superseding decision and a schema change to this field's
  // nullability — it is not supported by this MVP schema.
  visaStatusChanges VisaStatusHistory[] @relation("VisaStatusHistoryActor")

  @@map("user")
}

// Database-backed session (blueprint Section 4; ADR-001's "secure, HttpOnly,
// SameSite cookies and database-backed session state").
model Session {
  id        String   @id
  expiresAt DateTime
  token     String   @unique
  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt
  ipAddress String?
  userAgent String?

  userId String
  user   User   @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  @@map("session")
}

// One row per sign-in method linked to a User. For our credential (email +
// password) login, providerId = "credential" and `password` holds the
// Better Auth-hashed (scrypt) password — never a plaintext value.
model Account {
  id                    String    @id
  accountId             String
  providerId            String
  accessToken           String?
  refreshToken          String?
  idToken               String?
  accessTokenExpiresAt  DateTime?
  refreshTokenExpiresAt DateTime?
  scope                 String?
  password              String?
  createdAt             DateTime  @default(now())
  updatedAt             DateTime  @updatedAt

  userId String
  user   User   @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  @@map("account")
}

// Short-lived tokens (email verification, password reset, etc.).
model Verification {
  id         String    @id
  identifier String
  value      String
  expiresAt  DateTime
  createdAt  DateTime? @default(now())
  updatedAt  DateTime? @updatedAt

  @@map("verification")
}

// Staff-specific profile information linked to a User (blueprint Section
// 14.1). Deliberately minimal for this checkpoint (title/phone only) —
// User already owns name and email; this model must not duplicate either.
model StaffProfile {
  id        String   @id
  userId    String   @unique
  title     String?
  phone     String?
  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  user User @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  @@map("staff_profile")
}

// Append-only record of sensitive/security-relevant staff actions
// (blueprint Section 14.9; .claude/rules/backend.md Auditability;
// .claude/rules/database-security.md Audit Records). No role, including
// SYSTEM_ADMINISTRATOR, may modify or delete a row once written — the
// repository layer built in a later checkpoint must only ever INSERT here,
// never UPDATE or DELETE. `onDelete: Restrict` on the actor relation so an
// actor's User row can never be removed out from under an existing audit
// trail (accounts are deactivated, never deleted, under this model).
model AuditLog {
  id          String   @id
  actorId     String
  action      String
  entityType  String
  entityId    String
  beforeState Json?
  afterState  Json?
  createdAt   DateTime @default(now())

  actor User @relation(fields: [actorId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  @@index([actorId])
  @@index([entityType, entityId])
  @@index([createdAt])
  @@map("audit_log")
}

// --- Checkpoint 1: Lead / Client / LeadStatusHistory / StaffAssignment ---
// Schema only. No service layer, API, UI, or seed data. See the file header
// for what remains deliberately out of scope.

// The ten approved Lead lifecycle statuses (blueprint Section 6.1). Once a
// lead reaches CONVERTED_TO_CLIENT, further commercial progress is tracked
// on the Client's Proposal / ROS (Section 9), never as additional Lead
// statuses (Section 6.1's closing note).
enum LeadStatus {
  NEW
  UNDER_REVIEW
  CONTACTED
  CONSULTATION_SCHEDULED
  QUALIFIED
  CONVERTED_TO_CLIENT
  NOT_PROCEEDING
  DUPLICATE
  SPAM
  ARCHIVED
}

// An inquiry record prior to conversion (blueprint Section 5, Section 6;
// entity planning Section 14.2). A Lead is never auto-created into a
// Client, Booking, Payment plan, or Visa case (Section 5.1's non-automatic
// creation rule).
//
// `email`/`phone` hold contact details as submitted or recorded;
// `normalizedEmail`/`normalizedPhone` hold a lookup-normalized form of the
// same values for duplicate detection (Section 6.2). Matches must be
// surfaced for staff review, never silently rejected or merged, so these
// are indexed but deliberately not `@unique`
// (.claude/rules/database-security.md Constraints and Indexes).
//
// Field-level requiredness for contact fields (`email`/`phone`) beyond
// `fullName` is intentionally not enforced here: the blueprint does not
// define which contact channel(s) each intake source guarantees (public
// quote request vs. phone/walk-in/referral per Section 6.8), so exact
// required-field validation belongs at the service-layer Zod boundary
// (.claude/rules/architecture.md) once that intake contract is confirmed,
// not in the database schema now. `source` below is schema-required (NOT
// NULL) because every intake path — public or manual — always captures an
// originating channel (Section 6.6, Section 6.8).
model Lead {
  id     String     @id
  status LeadStatus @default(NEW)

  fullName String
  email    String?
  phone    String?

  // Lookup-normalized forms of email/phone, maintained by the service
  // layer (e.g. lowercased/trimmed email, digits-only phone) — see the
  // model doc comment above.
  normalizedEmail String?
  normalizedPhone String?

  // Free-text originating channel (blueprint Section 6.6) — deliberately
  // not an enum; the blueprint gives examples (quote request, package
  // planner, contact page, phone/walk-in/referral per Section 6.8) but does
  // not define a closed source list.
  source String

  notes String?

  // Set only by an explicit staff conversion action (Section 6.7); never
  // auto-populated. `onDelete: Restrict` so a Client can't be removed out
  // from under a Lead that documents its own conversion history.
  clientId String?
  client   Client? @relation(fields: [clientId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  statusHistory LeadStatusHistory[]
  assignments   StaffAssignment[]

  @@index([status])
  @@index([normalizedEmail])
  @@index([normalizedPhone])
  @@index([clientId])
  @@map("lead")
}

// Timestamped record of every Lead status change (blueprint Section 14.2).
// Append-only in practice: the repository layer built in a later checkpoint
// must only ever INSERT here, following AuditLog's convention above.
//
// `previousStatus` is nullable because a lead's first history row (its
// initial NEW status, whether created by public submission or manual staff
// entry per Section 6.8) has no prior status to record. `changedByUserId`
// is nullable for the same reason — a public-submission-created initial
// status has no staff actor.
model LeadStatusHistory {
  id String @id

  leadId String
  lead   Lead   @relation(fields: [leadId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  previousStatus LeadStatus?
  newStatus      LeadStatus

  // `onDelete: Restrict`: never silently drop the acting user's identity
  // off an existing history row (accounts are deactivated, never deleted,
  // per the AuditLog model's convention above).
  changedByUserId String?
  changedBy       User?   @relation("LeadStatusHistoryActor", fields: [changedByUserId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())

  @@index([leadId])
  @@index([changedByUserId])
  @@index([createdAt])
  @@map("lead_status_history")
}

// The business record for a party with an active or past commercial
// relationship (blueprint Section 5, Section 14.2). Distinct from both
// `User` (the login credential) and `ClientProfile` (the portal/profile
// extension created at account activation — Section 14.1; see that
// model's own doc comment below). A Client can exist without portal
// access, and is created or linked only through explicit lead conversion
// (Section 6.7) — never automatically.
//
// Deliberately excluded from this checkpoint: a client-status field/enum —
// blueprint Section 13.3 lists "Client status" as a record field, but the
// blueprint does not define an approved status list for it anywhere (unlike
// LeadStatus in Section 6.1; Section 16.2's open-decisions list does not
// yet carry this item either), so adding one now would be guessing.
// "Assigned staff member" (Section 13.3) is represented via
// `StaffAssignment` below, not a direct field, to avoid a
// second, competing source of truth for assignment. Proposals, bookings,
// payment records, documents, and support history (Section 13.3) are
// later-phase entities and are not modeled yet.
model Client {
  id String @id

  fullName String
  email    String?
  phone    String?

  // Lookup-normalized forms of email/phone — see the Lead model's doc
  // comment above; the same duplicate-detection rationale (Section 6.2)
  // applies when checking new leads against existing clients.
  normalizedEmail String?
  normalizedPhone String?

  // Optional profile fields, each directly justified by blueprint Section
  // 13.3's client-record field list, collected only when operationally
  // necessary (Section 13.3; .claude/rules/database-security.md Data
  // Minimization). `emergencyContact` is kept as one free-text field rather
  // than a structured name/phone split the blueprint doesn't itself define.
  address          String?
  nationality      String?
  dateOfBirth      DateTime? @db.Date
  emergencyContact String?

  notes String?

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  // Historical leads converted to, or later linked to, this Client — a
  // Client may be linked from multiple Lead rows over time.
  leads       Lead[]
  assignments StaffAssignment[]

  // Checkpoint 1 of the Client Portal Ownership Foundation (blueprint
  // Sections 4.6, 5, 7, 14.1, 14.2). Both optional/zero-or-one: a Client
  // may exist — and typically does, for a time — with neither a
  // PortalInvitation (Section 7.1's "Not Invited") nor a ClientProfile
  // (not yet activated). See each model's own doc comment below.
  clientProfile    ClientProfile?
  portalInvitation PortalInvitation?

  // Checkpoint 1 of the Proposal / ROS Schema Foundation (blueprint
  // Sections 5, 9, 14.4). A Client may have zero or more Proposals over
  // time (Section 5.2's conceptual relationship diagram).
  proposals Proposal[]

  // The Booking Schema Foundation schema-and-migration checkpoint
  // (blueprint Sections 5, 13.4, 14.5). A Client may have zero or more
  // Bookings over time, each created from one of this Client's accepted
  // ProposalVersions (see the Booking model doc comment below).
  bookings Booking[]

  // The Conversation Schema Foundation schema-and-migration checkpoint
  // (blueprint Sections 10, 10.1, 14.3). Every Conversation tied to this
  // Client over time — see the Conversation model doc comment below for
  // why `clientId` is a direct FK rather than derived through a related
  // Booking or Proposal.
  conversations Conversation[]

  // The Visa Case Schema Foundation checkpoint, Stage A (blueprint
  // Sections 5, 5.2, 13.8, 14.8; docs/HERITAGE_V3_DECISIONS_LOG.md D-017).
  // Per D-017, a Client has at most one VisaCase per Booking for the MVP
  // (see the VisaCase model doc comment below) but may still accumulate
  // more than one over time across different Bookings, hence the array.
  visaCases VisaCase[]

  @@index([normalizedEmail])
  @@index([normalizedPhone])
  @@map("client")
}

// Records which staff member is assigned to which Lead, Client, Booking, or
// VisaCase — the assignment-based access model (blueprint Section 4,
// Section 14.1). Extended to support Booking as of the Booking Schema
// Foundation schema-and-migration checkpoint (below). Extended to support
// VisaCase by the Visa Case Schema Foundation checkpoint
// (docs/HERITAGE_V3_DECISIONS_LOG.md D-017). Migration
// `20260717024618_visa_case_schema_foundation` added this column and its
// constraints (below) and has been applied to local `heritage_v3_dev`;
// `features/assignments`' `TargetKind` union/service/audit/authorization
// code remains deliberately untouched, matching how the Booking Schema
// Foundation checkpoint added `bookingId` to the schema before its own
// later, separate service-wiring checkpoint (D-015).
//
// Exactly one of `leadId` / `clientId` / `bookingId` must be non-null.
// Prisma's schema language cannot express a column-level XOR/CHECK
// constraint, so migration `20260716020734_booking_schema_foundation`
// ALTERs this table's existing CHECK constraint (added by create-only
// migration `20260714024613_lead_client_assignment_foundation`) rather
// than adding a second, conflicting one — dropping the old two-column
// constraint and adding a three-column replacement:
//   ALTER TABLE "staff_assignment"
//     DROP CONSTRAINT "staff_assignment_lead_xor_client";
//   ALTER TABLE "staff_assignment" ADD CONSTRAINT
//     "staff_assignment_lead_xor_client_xor_booking"
//     CHECK (num_nonnulls("leadId", "clientId", "bookingId") = 1);
// Do not rely on application code alone to hold this invariant.
// Migration-application status (which environments have actually run this
// migration) is tracked in docs/HERITAGE_V3_TASK_BOARD.md, not this file.
//
// Migration `20260717024618_visa_case_schema_foundation` extended this
// three-column CHECK to a four-column one — dropping the prior constraint
// and adding its replacement, the same mechanical pattern used for the
// two-to-three-column change above:
//   ALTER TABLE "staff_assignment"
//     DROP CONSTRAINT "staff_assignment_lead_xor_client_xor_booking";
//   ALTER TABLE "staff_assignment" ADD CONSTRAINT
//     "staff_assignment_lead_xor_client_xor_booking_xor_visa_case"
//     CHECK (num_nonnulls("leadId", "clientId", "bookingId", "visaCaseId") = 1);
// This four-column CHECK is applied and validated on local
// `heritage_v3_dev` — the database XOR constraint now covers `leadId`,
// `clientId`, `bookingId`, and `visaCaseId` there. Its application to
// staging or production must still be verified independently.
//
// `endedAt` is null while the assignment is active and is set once revoked,
// so assignment history is preserved rather than deleted
// (.claude/rules/admin-dashboard.md Destructive and Irreversible Actions).
// This schema also cannot express a partial unique index limiting a
// Lead/Client/Booking to at most one active assignment; migration
// `20260714024613_lead_client_assignment_foundation` already added this
// for Lead/Client:
//   CREATE UNIQUE INDEX "staff_assignment_active_lead_key"
//     ON "staff_assignment" ("leadId")
//     WHERE "endedAt" IS NULL AND "leadId" IS NOT NULL;
//   CREATE UNIQUE INDEX "staff_assignment_active_client_key"
//     ON "staff_assignment" ("clientId")
//     WHERE "endedAt" IS NULL AND "clientId" IS NOT NULL;
// Migration `20260716020734_booking_schema_foundation` adds the
// equivalent index for `bookingId`:
//   CREATE UNIQUE INDEX "staff_assignment_active_booking_key"
//     ON "staff_assignment" ("bookingId")
//     WHERE "endedAt" IS NULL AND "bookingId" IS NOT NULL;
// The same migration also added the equivalent partial unique index for
// it; `staff_assignment_active_visa_case_key` is applied on local
// `heritage_v3_dev` and now enforces at most one active assignment per
// VisaCase there:
//   CREATE UNIQUE INDEX "staff_assignment_active_visa_case_key"
//     ON "staff_assignment" ("visaCaseId")
//     WHERE "endedAt" IS NULL AND "visaCaseId" IS NOT NULL;
// Whether "at most one active assignment" should instead vary by an
// assignment type/role (e.g. a Travel Consultant and a Finance user each
// holding a concurrent active assignment on the same Client) is not defined
// by the blueprint yet — flag it as an open decision before relying on
// these indexes long-term; do not assume single-assignment permanently.
//
// Neither `assignedStaffId` nor `assignedByUserId` is schema-restricted to
// staff roles below — a foreign key can't constrain another table's column
// value. The future assignment-management service must reject any value
// that resolves to a CLIENT-role User (blueprint Section 4.7 scopes
// assignment-based access to Travel Consultant, Visa Documentation Staff,
// and Finance users only), the same way the invariants block above the
// User model documents equivalent deferred service-layer checks.
model StaffAssignment {
  id String @id

  // The staff member this assignment grants access to the target.
  assignedStaffId String
  assignedStaff   User   @relation("StaffAssignmentAssignee", fields: [assignedStaffId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  // The staff member who created this assignment. Blueprint Section 4.2
  // gives Admin / Manager the capability to manage lead/client/booking
  // assignments; whether Travel Consultants may also create assignments
  // (e.g. self-assigning a manually created lead, D-009(d)) is not stated
  // in the blueprint and is left an open decision, not assumed here.
  assignedByUserId String
  assignedBy       User   @relation("StaffAssignmentAssigner", fields: [assignedByUserId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  leadId String?
  lead   Lead?   @relation(fields: [leadId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  clientId String?
  client   Client? @relation(fields: [clientId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  // Added by the Booking Schema Foundation schema-and-migration checkpoint
  // — see the model doc comment above for the CHECK-constraint and
  // partial-unique-index changes migration
  // `20260716020734_booking_schema_foundation` makes for this column.
  bookingId String?
  booking   Booking? @relation(fields: [bookingId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  // Added by the Visa Case Schema Foundation checkpoint — see the model
  // doc comment above for the CHECK-constraint and partial-unique-index
  // changes migration `20260717024618_visa_case_schema_foundation` makes
  // for this column.
  visaCaseId String?
  visaCase   VisaCase? @relation(fields: [visaCaseId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  createdAt DateTime  @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime  @updatedAt
  endedAt   DateTime?

  // Authorization/active-assignment lookups: "what is this staff member
  // currently assigned to" and "who is currently assigned to this
  // Lead/Client/Booking/VisaCase" both filter on endedAt IS NULL.
  @@index([assignedStaffId, endedAt])
  @@index([leadId, endedAt])
  @@index([clientId, endedAt])
  @@index([bookingId, endedAt])
  @@index([visaCaseId, endedAt])
  @@index([assignedByUserId])
  @@map("staff_assignment")
}

// --- Checkpoint 1: Client Portal Ownership Foundation (ClientProfile / PortalInvitation) ---
// Schema only. No invitation/activation service, token generation/hashing,
// email delivery, account-creation code, API route, UI, or seed data. See
// the file header for the full list of what remains deliberately deferred.

// The six statuses a PortalInvitation row can actually persist (blueprint
// Section 7.1). "Not Invited" — Section 7.1's seventh table row — is
// deliberately not a value here: it is represented by the absence of any
// PortalInvitation row for a Client (see that model's doc comment), never
// by a status value, so a NOT_INVITED member is never added to this enum.
enum PortalInvitationStatus {
  INVITATION_PREPARED
  INVITATION_SENT
  INVITATION_OPENED
  ACCOUNT_ACTIVATED
  INVITATION_EXPIRED
  INVITATION_REVOKED
}

// The portal/profile extension for a Client (blueprint Section 14.1),
// created only once — at the moment a PortalInvitation is successfully
// redeemed and the linked User account is activated ("created at account
// activation... does not exist before activation"). Distinct from both
// `User` (the login credential) and `Client` (the business record) per
// Section 5's Core Domain Concepts separation rule, and deliberately does
// not copy any Client identity/contact field (fullName, email, phone,
// etc.) — it exists only to hold the one-to-one User↔Client activation
// link, plus whatever portal-only profile state a later checkpoint adds.
//
// The linked `user` must hold `Role.CLIENT`. Prisma's schema language
// cannot express a cross-table "this foreign key's target row must have
// column X = Y" constraint, so that invariant is not, and cannot be,
// enforced here. The future activation service must verify it
// transactionally — inside the same transaction that creates this row —
// before ever writing a ClientProfile; do not rely on application code
// outside that transaction to hold this invariant.
//
// `onDelete: Restrict` on both `user` and `client`: neither the User
// account nor the Client business record this profile links can be
// removed out from under it, so activation/ownership history is never
// silently destroyed (.claude/rules/database-security.md's referential-
// integrity rule).
model ClientProfile {
  id String @id

  userId String @unique
  user   User   @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  clientId String @unique
  client   Client @relation(fields: [clientId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  // Checkpoint 1 of the Proposal / ROS Schema Foundation (blueprint
  // Sections 9, 14.4). Every portal-based ProposalAcceptance response this
  // activated client account has made — never populated for externally
  // recorded responses (Section 9.1), which are attributed to a staff User
  // instead (see ProposalAcceptance below).
  proposalAcceptances ProposalAcceptance[]

  // The Conversation Schema Foundation schema-and-migration checkpoint
  // (blueprint Sections 10, 10.1, 14.3). `conversationParticipations`:
  // every Conversation this activated client account currently or
  // formerly participated in (CLIENT capacity — see
  // ConversationParticipant's own doc comment). `authoredMessages`: every
  // Message this client account sent — never populated for a
  // staff-authored Message (see the Message model doc comment below).
  conversationParticipations ConversationParticipant[]
  authoredMessages           Message[]

  @@map("client_profile")
}

// The time-limited, single-use invitation record described in blueprint
// Section 7. `clientId` is `@unique`, which prevents two simultaneously
// persisted PortalInvitation rows for the same Client — it does not, and
// cannot, prevent a delete-then-reinsert sequence from producing a second
// row over time; a unique constraint only guarantees at most one row at a
// time, not that the row is never replaced. A resend (Section 7.2:
// "Resendable without duplication... invalidates the prior token and
// returns the status to Invitation Sent, without creating a duplicate...
// PortalInvitation record") must therefore UPDATE this same row in place
// (new `tokenHash`, new `expiresAt`, status reset to INVITATION_SENT). The
// future repository/service layer must preserve this row as the Client's
// invitation history and must never delete-and-recreate it during a
// resend — that discipline, like every other lifecycle rule below, is
// enforced by that future service, not by this schema alone. A Client
// with no PortalInvitation row at all is "Not Invited" (Section 7.1) —
// see PortalInvitationStatus for why there is no corresponding status
// value.
//
// `tokenHash` stores only a hash of the invitation token, never the raw,
// replayable token itself (.claude/rules/database-security.md's
// "Protecting Sensitive Data": invitation tokens must be "stored in a way
// that a database read alone can't be replayed as a valid token"), and is
// itself `@unique` so a hash collision can never silently let one token
// activate two invitations. Raw token generation and its hashing are
// implemented by the future invitation service, not modeled or performed
// here.
//
// `expiresAt` stores only the expiration timestamp; this schema does not
// invent or default an invitation validity duration — blueprint Section
// 16.2 explicitly leaves the exact expiration duration an open decision.
//
// This is schema only: single-use redemption, expiration processing,
// resend, activation, and every status transition are enforced
// transactionally by the future invitation/activation service, not by
// this schema. Resend and revocation AuditLog entries (blueprint Section
// 7.3: actor, timestamp, and — for revocation — a reason) are likewise
// written by that future service, not here.
model PortalInvitation {
  id String @id

  clientId String @unique
  client   Client @relation(fields: [clientId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  status PortalInvitationStatus @default(INVITATION_PREPARED)

  tokenHash String @unique

  expiresAt DateTime

  sentAt      DateTime?
  openedAt    DateTime?
  activatedAt DateTime?
  revokedAt   DateTime?

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  @@index([status])
  @@index([expiresAt])
  @@map("portal_invitation")
}

// --- Checkpoint 1: Proposal / ROS Schema Foundation (Proposal / ProposalVersion / ProposalAcceptance) ---
// The repository contains create-only migration
// `20260715055859_proposal_ros_foundation`, which creates these tables and
// contains both hand-written PostgreSQL statements documented below. This
// file does not claim whether that migration has been applied to any
// environment (local, staging, or production) —
// docs/HERITAGE_V3_TASK_BOARD.md remains the source for verified
// environment/migration-application status. No repository layer, service
// layer, API route, client portal or admin dashboard UI, tests, or seed
// data exists either. See the file header for the full list of what
// remains deliberately deferred.

// The three response terms approved in blueprint Section 9, "used
// consistently across the platform" — not a broader proposal-status
// lifecycle. This is deliberately not a closed value for *how* a response
// was delivered — see ProposalAcceptance.responseMethod below, which is a
// separate, open-ended field.
enum ProposalResponseType {
  ACCEPT
  DECLINE
  REQUEST_CHANGES
}

// The ROS (Rundown of Service) record for a Client (blueprint Sections 5,
// 9, 14.4), created only through explicit staff action for an
// already-converted Client (Section 6.7) — never automatically (Section
// 5.1's non-automatic creation rule). Deliberately carries no status field
// of its own: its entire lifecycle is expressed by its ProposalVersion
// rows (draft / current-visible / superseded — see that model's doc
// comment) and by ProposalAcceptance responses, so a second, competing
// status here would be redundant. No proposal content (itinerary,
// quotation, pricing, currency) lives on this model or on ProposalVersion
// in this checkpoint — see the file header for why, and D-002 for the
// still-unresolved currency decision this defers around.
model Proposal {
  id String @id

  // `onDelete: Restrict`: a Client can never be removed out from under a
  // Proposal that documents its commercial history, matching this
  // schema's established convention (Lead.clientId, ClientProfile.clientId,
  // PortalInvitation.clientId).
  clientId String
  client   Client @relation(fields: [clientId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  versions ProposalVersion[]

  // The Conversation Schema Foundation schema-and-migration checkpoint
  // (blueprint Sections 10, 10.1, 14.3). Every Conversation that names this
  // Proposal as its (at most one, per this checkpoint) related record —
  // see the Conversation model doc comment below.
  conversations Conversation[]

  @@index([clientId])
  @@map("proposal")
}

// An individual versioned draft/revision of a Proposal (blueprint Sections
// 9, 14.4). Every edit after the first creates a new ProposalVersion
// rather than overwriting the previous one (Section 9); existing rows are
// never updated to change their content and never deleted by any future
// repository method — full revision history is retained permanently. This
// checkpoint models only version identity and lifecycle state, not
// proposal content: no itinerary, quotation, line-item, pricing, or
// currency field exists here (see the file header) — a later checkpoint
// adds them once their shape is approved.
//
// Lifecycle is expressed by two independent, monotonic timestamps rather
// than a status enum:
//
// - `clientVisibleAt` — null while this version is an unpublished
//   consultant draft (Section 9: the client "sees only the current
//   client-visible version"); set once this version has been shown to the
//   client at least once ("published"). Multiple unpublished drafts
//   (`clientVisibleAt IS NULL`) may coexist for the same Proposal — this
//   checkpoint deliberately does not add an "at most one active draft"
//   constraint; nothing in the blueprint requires it.
// - `supersededAt` — null means only "not superseded"; it does not by
//   itself mean "the latest," "active," or "current" version, since
//   multiple unpublished drafts (`clientVisibleAt IS NULL`, see above) may
//   simultaneously have `supersededAt IS NULL`. Once set, it means this
//   specific version has been superseded (a newer version replaced it) or
//   abandoned (a never-published draft was dropped in favor of a
//   different one). Never cleared once set.
//
// Combining both fields distinguishes every state the blueprint requires:
// unpublished draft (`clientVisibleAt` null, `supersededAt` null); current
// client-visible version (`clientVisibleAt` set, `supersededAt` null —
// Section 9's "current client-visible version"); superseded version
// (`supersededAt` set, regardless of `clientVisibleAt`).
//
// "Accepted/locked" (Section 9: "once a version is accepted, it becomes
// locked — it cannot be edited further") is deliberately NOT a third
// stored field here. It is derived from this version's ProposalAcceptance
// (see that model's `proposalVersionId @unique` below — at most one final
// response per version): a version is accepted/locked exactly when its
// related ProposalAcceptance exists and has `responseType = ACCEPT`. A
// separate stored `acceptedAt`/`lockedAt` timestamp was deliberately
// rejected to avoid two fields ever representing the same acceptance
// moment and drifting apart — `ProposalAcceptance.respondedAt` is the one
// source of truth for when that happened. Enforcing "cannot be edited
// further" is a future service-layer concern once content fields and an
// update path exist; this checkpoint has no editable content field for
// that rule to protect yet.
//
// Prisma's schema language cannot express "at most one current
// client-visible version per Proposal" as a column-level constraint —
// migration `20260715055859_proposal_ros_foundation` adds this raw SQL by
// hand:
//   CREATE UNIQUE INDEX "proposal_version_current_client_visible_key"
//     ON "proposal_version" ("proposalId")
//     WHERE "clientVisibleAt" IS NOT NULL AND "supersededAt" IS NULL;
// This index also serves as the race-safety backstop for the future
// "publish" service operation (supersede the current version, then mark
// the draft as client-visible, in one transaction): if that operation is
// ever raced by a concurrent publish, the later commit fails on this
// unique violation instead of silently producing two simultaneously
// current versions. This file does not claim whether that migration has
// been applied to any environment — see the file header.
model ProposalVersion {
  id String @id

  proposalId String
  proposal   Proposal @relation(fields: [proposalId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  versionNumber Int

  // The staff member who authored this specific version (Section 9: "A
  // Travel Consultant creates the initial ROS draft... each edit... creates
  // a new version"). `onDelete: Restrict`: never drop this attribution —
  // accounts are deactivated, never deleted, per this schema's established
  // convention (LeadStatusHistory.changedByUserId, StaffAssignment).
  //
  // This FK only records who authored the version — it cannot enforce
  // proposal-author eligibility or that `createdByUser` is actually
  // assigned to this Proposal's Client. The future Proposal service must
  // enforce the approved role and assignment rules from blueprint Sections
  // 4.2, 4.3, and 9 before writing this field, the same way
  // `ProposalAcceptance.recordedByStaffUserId` below documents for
  // externally recorded responses. This schema comment does not itself
  // grant Admin / Manager permission to author or revise ProposalVersions:
  // Section 9 (and Section 4.3's capability list) currently assigns
  // Proposal/ROS preparation and revision to Travel Consultants; any
  // additional authoring permission (e.g. for Admin / Manager) must come
  // from an explicit approved rule, not be assumed from this FK's type.
  createdByUserId String
  createdByUser   User   @relation(fields: [createdByUserId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  clientVisibleAt DateTime?
  supersededAt    DateTime?

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  acceptance ProposalAcceptance?

  // The Booking Schema Foundation schema-and-migration checkpoint
  // (blueprint Sections 5, 5.2, 9, 13.4, 14.5). At most one Booking may be
  // created from this specific ProposalVersion — see the Booking model's
  // `proposalVersionId @unique` field and doc comment below.
  booking Booking?

  @@unique([proposalId, versionNumber])
  @@index([createdByUserId])
  @@map("proposal_version")
}

// The record of a client's response to a specific ProposalVersion — Accept,
// Decline, or Request Changes (blueprint Sections 9, 14.4) — always
// including a response timestamp. `proposalVersionId` is `@unique`: at
// most one final response per ProposalVersion. Only the current
// client-visible version may receive a response
// (`clientVisibleAt IS NOT NULL AND supersededAt IS NULL` — see
// ProposalVersion above) — the database cannot verify that a given version
// is "current" at the moment of insert (that fact depends on the state of
// other rows), so the future service layer must check it transactionally
// before writing this row.
//
// Exactly one of two complete, mutually exclusive attribution paths
// applies to every row — a portal response or an externally recorded one
// (Section 9.1) — never a mix of both and never neither:
//
// - Portal path — `respondingClientProfileId` (the durable client-portal
//   identity, blueprint Section 14.1) plus `respondingSessionIdAtResponse`
//   (below). `responseMethod`, `evidenceReference`, and
//   `recordedByStaffUserId` are all null.
// - External path (Section 9.1) — `recordedByStaffUserId` (the staff
//   member who entered the response), `responseMethod` (the channel, e.g.
//   phone/email/in person), and `evidenceReference` (a pointer or
//   identifier — never a full copy of correspondence, consistent with
//   `.claude/rules/database-security.md`'s data-minimization principle).
//   `respondingClientProfileId` and `respondingSessionIdAtResponse` are
//   both null. Section 9.1 restricts *who* may record an external
//   response (only the Travel Consultant assigned to the Client, or an
//   Admin / Manager) — not schema-expressible; the future service layer
//   must enforce it, reusing/extending the existing `canAccessClient`
//   authorization foundation
//   (apps/web/src/features/assignments/authorization.ts).
//
// `responseMethod` is deliberately `String`, not a closed enum — the
// blueprint gives only examples ("e.g., phone, email, in person"), not an
// approved closed list, matching this schema's established precedent
// (Lead.source).
//
// Prisma's schema language cannot express "exactly one complete
// attribution path" as a column-level constraint — migration
// `20260715055859_proposal_ros_foundation` adds this raw SQL by hand:
//   ALTER TABLE "proposal_acceptance"
//   ADD CONSTRAINT "proposal_acceptance_response_path"
//   CHECK (
//     (
//       "respondingClientProfileId" IS NOT NULL
//       AND "respondingSessionIdAtResponse" IS NOT NULL
//       AND "recordedByStaffUserId" IS NULL
//       AND "responseMethod" IS NULL
//       AND "evidenceReference" IS NULL
//     )
//     OR
//     (
//       "recordedByStaffUserId" IS NOT NULL
//       AND "responseMethod" IS NOT NULL
//       AND "evidenceReference" IS NOT NULL
//       AND "respondingClientProfileId" IS NULL
//       AND "respondingSessionIdAtResponse" IS NULL
//     )
//   );
// This file does not claim whether that migration has been applied to any
// environment — see the file header.
model ProposalAcceptance {
  id String @id

  proposalVersionId String          @unique
  proposalVersion   ProposalVersion @relation(fields: [proposalVersionId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  responseType ProposalResponseType
  respondedAt  DateTime

  // Portal path. `onDelete: Restrict` on `respondingClientProfile`: never
  // drop a client's identity out from under their own recorded response,
  // matching this schema's established convention.
  respondingClientProfileId String?
  respondingClientProfile   ClientProfile? @relation(fields: [respondingClientProfileId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  // An immutable snapshot of Better Auth's `Session.id` at the moment of
  // response — never `Session.token` (the actual replayable session
  // credential; that value must never be persisted here or anywhere
  // outside Better Auth's own `session` table). Deliberately NOT a
  // `@relation` to Session: Session is Better Auth's own ephemeral
  // session-management table (see this file's earlier note on the
  // Session/Account/Verification models), not a Heritage domain entity,
  // and it is routinely cleaned up on logout/expiry. A live FK here would
  // either block that cleanup (`Restrict`) or silently destroy this
  // permanent response record when a session row is swept (`Cascade`) —
  // both unacceptable. Storing only the id as a plain, unvalidated scalar
  // lets normal session deletion proceed untouched while this row keeps a
  // permanent historical breadcrumb, the same way `AuditLog.beforeState`/
  // `afterState` are unvalidated historical snapshots rather than live
  // relations. The future service layer verifies session/client ownership
  // (that the live, already-authenticated session's `userId` matches
  // `respondingClientProfile.userId`, and that `respondingClientProfile`
  // owns this response's Proposal's Client) at write time, from the live
  // request context — never by re-querying this column afterward.
  respondingSessionIdAtResponse String?

  // External fallback path (Section 9.1). `onDelete: Restrict` on
  // `recordedByStaffUser`: never drop the acting staff member's identity
  // off an existing response record, matching this schema's established
  // convention (LeadStatusHistory.changedByUserId, AuditLog.actorId).
  recordedByStaffUserId String?
  recordedByStaffUser   User?   @relation(fields: [recordedByStaffUserId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)
  responseMethod        String?
  evidenceReference     String?

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())

  @@index([respondingClientProfileId])
  @@index([recordedByStaffUserId])
  @@index([respondedAt])
  @@map("proposal_acceptance")
}

// --- Booking Schema Foundation: schema-and-migration checkpoint ---
// Adds Booking and BookingStatusHistory, and extends StaffAssignment (see
// that model's updated doc comment above) so Booking is a supported
// assignment target. Migration `20260716020734_booking_schema_foundation`
// contains this checkpoint's schema operations and PostgreSQL constraints;
// migration-application status (which environments have actually run it)
// is tracked in docs/HERITAGE_V3_TASK_BOARD.md. No repository layer,
// service layer, API route, client portal or admin dashboard UI, tests, or
// seed data exists either — these remain deferred to future checkpoints.
// See the file header for the full list of what remains deliberately
// deferred (TourPackage as a catalogue entity, ItineraryVersion and
// structured itinerary content, Booking total price/currency, and
// structured per-traveller records).

// The ten "suggested" booking statuses (blueprint Section 13.4) adopted as
// the working enum, the same way LeadStatus (Section 6.1) was adopted
// directly from its blueprint table.
enum BookingStatus {
  DRAFT
  PENDING_CONFIRMATION
  CONFIRMED
  IN_PREPARATION
  DOCUMENTS_REQUIRED
  VISA_PROCESSING
  READY_FOR_TRAVEL
  IN_PROGRESS
  COMPLETED
  CANCELLED
}

// The confirmed commercial engagement created from an accepted
// ProposalVersion by an explicit staff action (blueprint Sections 5, 5.1,
// 5.2, 9, 13.4, 14.5) — never automatically (Section 5.1's non-automatic
// creation rule).
//
// `clientId` is a direct FK (mirroring this schema's established
// Proposal.clientId convention) rather than something derived solely by
// walking `proposalVersion.proposal.clientId`. Service-layer invariant for
// later implementation, not enforced by a database trigger in this
// checkpoint: `Booking.clientId` must always equal the Client connected
// through `Booking.proposalVersion.proposal.clientId`. The future
// Booking-creation service must verify this transactionally at write time,
// the same way other cross-row invariants in this schema (e.g. "is this
// ProposalVersion actually the current client-visible one") are deferred
// to the service layer rather than expressed as a schema constraint.
//
// `proposalVersionId` is `@unique`: at most one Booking may be created
// from a given ProposalVersion. The database cannot verify that the
// referenced ProposalVersion actually has an ACCEPT ProposalAcceptance
// (Section 9) — like ProposalAcceptance's own "is this the current
// client-visible version" check, that fact depends on the state of other
// rows, so the future Booking-creation service must verify it
// transactionally before writing this row.
//
// `bookingReference` is the human-facing booking number and is `@unique`.
//
// `tourPackageName` is deliberately not a foreign key to any catalogue
// entity — TourPackage (blueprint Section 14.5) remains deferred (see the
// file header). This field is only an optional, point-in-time snapshot of
// the tour/package name at booking time, not a live catalogue relation.
//
// `travelStartDate`/`travelEndDate`, `travelerCount`, and the free-text
// service/notes fields below are all nullable: booking details may not yet
// be known while `status` is DRAFT (blueprint Section 13.4 lists them as
// booking fields without stating which are required from creation).
// `internalNotes` and `clientVisibleNotes` both come from the Booking
// field list in blueprint Section 13.4 ("Internal notes" / "Client-visible
// notes"). Preventing clients from ever reading `internalNotes` is a
// future authorization responsibility for the API/service layer, not
// something this schema itself restricts.
//
// Migration `20260716020734_booking_schema_foundation` adds two CHECK
// constraints Prisma's schema language cannot express:
//   ALTER TABLE "booking" ADD CONSTRAINT "booking_traveler_count_positive"
//     CHECK ("travelerCount" IS NULL OR "travelerCount" > 0);
//   ALTER TABLE "booking" ADD CONSTRAINT "booking_travel_dates_order"
//     CHECK (
//       "travelStartDate" IS NULL OR "travelEndDate" IS NULL
//       OR "travelStartDate" <= "travelEndDate"
//     );
model Booking {
  id String @id

  bookingReference String @unique

  // `onDelete: Restrict`: a Client can never be removed out from under a
  // Booking that documents its own commercial history, matching this
  // schema's established convention (Lead.clientId, Proposal.clientId,
  // etc.).
  clientId String
  client   Client @relation(fields: [clientId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  // `onDelete: Restrict`: never drop the specific accepted ProposalVersion
  // a Booking was created from, matching this schema's established
  // convention. See the model doc comment above for the `@unique` and
  // client-consistency invariants this field carries.
  proposalVersionId String          @unique
  proposalVersion   ProposalVersion @relation(fields: [proposalVersionId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  status BookingStatus @default(DRAFT)

  // Point-in-time snapshot only — see the model doc comment above.
  tourPackageName String?

  destination String?

  travelStartDate DateTime? @db.Date
  travelEndDate   DateTime? @db.Date

  travelerCount Int?

  includedServices   String?
  excludedServices   String?
  specialRequests    String?
  internalNotes      String?
  clientVisibleNotes String?

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  statusHistory    BookingStatusHistory[]
  staffAssignments StaffAssignment[]

  // The Conversation Schema Foundation schema-and-migration checkpoint
  // (blueprint Sections 10, 10.1, 14.3). Every Conversation that names this
  // Booking as its (at most one, per this checkpoint) related record — see
  // the Conversation model doc comment below.
  conversations Conversation[]

  // The Visa Case Schema Foundation checkpoint, Stage A (blueprint
  // Sections 5, 5.2, 13.8, 14.8; docs/HERITAGE_V3_DECISIONS_LOG.md D-017).
  // Zero or one, per D-017's MVP granularity decision — see the VisaCase
  // model doc comment below for the `bookingId @unique` field that backs
  // this and why multiple/historical VisaCases per Booking are out of
  // scope.
  visaCase VisaCase?

  @@index([clientId])
  @@index([status])
  @@map("booking")
}

// Timestamped record of every Booking status change (blueprint Sections
// 5, 13.4; .claude/rules/database-security.md Identifiers and Timestamps;
// .claude/rules/backend.md Auditability), mirroring LeadStatusHistory's
// convention. Append-only in practice: the repository layer built in a
// later checkpoint must only ever INSERT here.
//
// `changedByUserId` here is required, unlike
// `LeadStatusHistory.changedByUserId` (nullable, because a lead's initial
// NEW status may originate from an unauthenticated public submission with
// no staff actor). Booking creation is an explicit staff action (blueprint
// Section 5.1). Booking status changes require actor/timestamp
// auditability (.claude/rules/backend.md Auditability). Making this field
// required is the approved schema policy for this checkpoint.
//
// `previousStatus` is nullable for the same reason as LeadStatusHistory's:
// a Booking's first history row (its initial DRAFT status) has no prior
// status to record.
//
// Migration `20260716020734_booking_schema_foundation` adds one CHECK
// constraint Prisma cannot express:
//   ALTER TABLE "booking_status_history"
//   ADD CONSTRAINT "booking_status_history_status_changed"
//   CHECK ("previousStatus" IS NULL OR "previousStatus" != "newStatus");
model BookingStatusHistory {
  id String @id

  bookingId String
  booking   Booking @relation(fields: [bookingId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  previousStatus BookingStatus?
  newStatus      BookingStatus

  // `onDelete: Restrict`: never drop the acting staff member's identity off
  // an existing history row, matching this schema's established
  // convention (LeadStatusHistory.changedByUserId, AuditLog.actorId). See
  // the model doc comment above for why this is required, not nullable.
  changedByUserId String
  changedBy       User   @relation("BookingStatusHistoryActor", fields: [changedByUserId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())

  @@index([bookingId, createdAt])
  @@index([changedByUserId])
  @@index([createdAt])
  @@map("booking_status_history")
}

// --- Conversation Schema Foundation: schema-and-migration checkpoint ---
// Adds ConversationCategory, MessageVisibility, ConversationParticipantRole,
// Conversation, ConversationParticipant, Message, and MessageAttachment
// (blueprint Sections 4.2-4.6, 9.1, 10, 10.1, 10.2, 10.3, 13.9, 14.3;
// docs/HERITAGE_V3_DECISIONS_LOG.md D-016). Split across two migrations —
// see D-016 for why: `20260717010445_conversation_schema_foundation`
// (tables, enums, standard indexes, foreign keys) and
// `20260717010520_conversation_schema_constraints` (every hand-added
// PostgreSQL CHECK constraint and partial unique index Prisma's schema
// language cannot express on its own). Both were successfully applied to
// local `heritage_v3_dev` on July 17, 2026, and `prisma migrate status`
// subsequently reported all 8 migrations applied and the schema up to
// date. Application to staging or production must still be verified
// independently — migration-application status per environment is tracked
// in docs/HERITAGE_V3_TASK_BOARD.md, not this file. No repository layer,
// service layer, API route, admin dashboard or client portal UI, tests, or
// seed data exists yet. In particular, this checkpoint deliberately does
// NOT implement:
//
// - Conversation/Message authorization. The future enforcement checkpoint
//   must account for all of: Admin/Manager's full, unconditional
//   visibility into every Conversation (Section 10.1 — a role-wide grant,
//   never an inserted ConversationParticipant row, matching
//   ADMIN_MANAGER's existing assignment-free treatment in
//   `canAccessClient`, apps/web/src/features/assignments/authorization.ts);
//   a CLIENT actor's own ownership of the Conversation's Client (via
//   ClientProfile, matching `canAccessClient`'s existing ownership check)
//   together with their explicit ConversationParticipant membership; a
//   TRAVEL_CONSULTANT's active Client/Booking assignment
//   (`StaffAssignment.endedAt IS NULL`); and explicit
//   ConversationParticipant membership for FINANCE_ACCOUNTING and
//   VISA_DOCUMENTATION actors, who have no assignment-based path onto a
//   Conversation at all. Conversation authorization must never be
//   described or implemented as "participant rows alone" — Admin/Manager's
//   visibility, and possibly a Travel Consultant's, may need to hold
//   without any ConversationParticipant row existing for them; whether
//   Travel Consultant access requires an explicit participant row or
//   active Client/Booking assignment alone suffices (as it already does
//   for Booking read/status access, D-014/D-015) is left an open decision
//   for that future checkpoint.
// - Server-side exclusion of INTERNAL_NOTE messages from every
//   client-facing query — never a client-side filter
//   (.claude/rules/admin-dashboard.md Visibility Scoping).
// - The cross-table client-consistency checks noted on the Conversation
//   model doc comment below (`relatedBooking.clientId`/
//   `relatedProposal.clientId` must equal `Conversation.clientId`; a
//   CLIENT participant must belong to `Conversation.clientId`).
// - Section 10.3's email notification delivery, and attachment malware
//   scanning / signed-expiring-URL issuance (Section 12.3).
//
// See each model's own doc comment below for further detail.

// The eight closed categories a Conversation may belong to (blueprint
// Section 10.2), adopted directly as the working enum, the same way
// LeadStatus (Section 6.1) and BookingStatus (Section 13.4) were each
// adopted directly from their own blueprint list.
enum ConversationCategory {
  GENERAL_INQUIRY
  PROPOSAL_ROS
  BOOKING
  PAYMENT
  DOCUMENTS
  VISA
  TRAVEL_PREPARATION
  TECHNICAL_SUPPORT
}

// Blueprint Section 10.1's "client-visible messages vs. internal staff
// notes" distinction. Modeled as a two-value enum, not a boolean, matching
// this schema's convention of naming blueprint-given terms directly
// (ProposalResponseType, PortalInvitationStatus) rather than encoding them
// as an unnamed boolean. Internal notes must never be exposed on the
// client portal (Section 10.1) — enforced by the future service/query
// layer on every client-facing read, never by client-side filtering
// (.claude/rules/admin-dashboard.md Visibility Scoping); see the Message
// model doc comment below for the one database-level restriction this
// schema does add (a client-authored message can never be INTERNAL_NOTE).
enum MessageVisibility {
  CLIENT_VISIBLE
  INTERNAL_NOTE
}

// The participant capacities blueprint Section 10.1 actually documents:
// the assigned Travel Consultant by default, plus an optional Finance
// participant and/or optional Visa Documentation participant "when
// relevant," and the Client themself (Section 4.6: clients "send and
// receive Support & Messages for their own records"). Deliberately does
// NOT include an ADMIN_MANAGER value: Section 10.1 describes Admin/
// Manager's full visibility into every Conversation as a role-wide grant,
// not participation in a specific thread — the same way `canAccessClient`
// grants ADMIN_MANAGER access without an assignment row
// (apps/web/src/features/assignments/authorization.ts). The future
// conversation-authorization checkpoint must implement that visibility as
// a role check, never by inserting a ConversationParticipant row for every
// Admin/Manager account. See ConversationParticipant's own doc comment
// below for how this enum interacts with the staffUserId/clientProfileId
// identity split.
enum ConversationParticipantRole {
  CLIENT
  TRAVEL_CONSULTANT
  FINANCE_ACCOUNTING
  VISA_DOCUMENTATION
}

// A message thread tied to a Client (blueprint Sections 10, 10.1, 14.3).
// Blueprint Section 10 does not define an exact conversation-creation
// policy — who may create a Conversation, and whether a client may
// self-initiate one for particular categories (e.g. Technical Support)
// versus every category requiring staff to open it — so this schema does
// not assume or encode one. That policy, and its authorization, are
// deferred to the future conversation-enforcement checkpoint.
//
// `clientId` is a direct FK, mirroring this schema's established
// Lead.clientId/Proposal.clientId/Booking.clientId convention, rather than
// something derivable only by walking a related Booking or Proposal —
// necessary because a Conversation may have no related record at all (e.g.
// a General Inquiry or Technical Support category conversation, Section
// 10.2).
//
// `relatedBookingId`/`relatedProposalId`/`relatedVisaCaseId` are all
// optional, and this checkpoint models **at most one** related record:
// Section 10.1 says a Conversation is "typically tied to... a specific
// booking, proposal, or case" — a soft, typical link, not a required one,
// and nothing in the blueprint states a Conversation may reference more
// than one related record simultaneously. `relatedVisaCaseId` was added by
// the Visa Case Schema Foundation checkpoint
// (docs/HERITAGE_V3_DECISIONS_LOG.md D-017). `onDelete: Restrict` on all
// three: never drop a Booking, Proposal, or VisaCase out from under a
// Conversation that references it, matching this schema's established
// convention.
//
// Prisma's schema language cannot express "at most one of these nullable
// columns is non-null" as a column-level constraint — migration
// `20260717010520_conversation_schema_constraints` originally added the
// two-column version of this raw SQL by hand:
//   ALTER TABLE "conversation" ADD CONSTRAINT
//     "conversation_related_record_exclusive"
//     CHECK (num_nonnulls("relatedBookingId", "relatedProposalId") <= 1);
// Migration `20260717024618_visa_case_schema_foundation` replaced it with
// the three-column version below, applied on local `heritage_v3_dev` —
// `conversation_related_record_exclusive` now covers `relatedBookingId`,
// `relatedProposalId`, and `relatedVisaCaseId` there:
//   ALTER TABLE "conversation"
//     DROP CONSTRAINT "conversation_related_record_exclusive";
//   ALTER TABLE "conversation" ADD CONSTRAINT
//     "conversation_related_record_exclusive"
//     CHECK (num_nonnulls("relatedBookingId", "relatedProposalId", "relatedVisaCaseId") <= 1);
// Its application to staging or production must still be verified
// independently. The related conversation-creation/messaging service
// enforcement described below remains deferred regardless.
//
// Service-layer invariants for later implementation, not enforced by any
// database constraint in this checkpoint (the database cannot verify a
// fact that depends on the state of other rows, matching this schema's
// established precedent for Booking.clientId / ProposalVersion's "current
// version" checks):
//   - `relatedBooking.clientId` must equal `Conversation.clientId`.
//   - `relatedProposal.clientId` must equal `Conversation.clientId`.
//   - `relatedVisaCase.clientId` must equal `Conversation.clientId`.
//   - a CLIENT-role `ConversationParticipant` on this Conversation must
//     resolve (via ClientProfile) to this exact `Conversation.clientId`.
// The future Conversation-creation/messaging service must verify each of
// these transactionally at write time — skipping them risks a cross-client
// data leak, which `.claude/rules/client-portal.md` treats as critical
// severity.
//
// Deliberately excluded from this checkpoint: a status/lifecycle field
// (open vs. resolved/closed) — blueprint Section 10 defines no such list,
// unlike LeadStatus/BookingStatus/PortalInvitationStatus, so none is
// invented; a subject/title field — not described anywhere in Section
// 10.1's field list; and a denormalized `lastMessageAt` — not documented,
// and would itself need service-layer maintenance this checkpoint does not
// add.
model Conversation {
  id String @id

  clientId String
  client   Client @relation(fields: [clientId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  category ConversationCategory

  relatedBookingId String?
  relatedBooking   Booking? @relation(fields: [relatedBookingId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  relatedProposalId String?
  relatedProposal   Proposal? @relation(fields: [relatedProposalId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  // Added by the Visa Case Schema Foundation checkpoint — see the model
  // doc comment above for the exclusivity-constraint replacement migration
  // `20260717024618_visa_case_schema_foundation` makes for this column.
  relatedVisaCaseId String?
  relatedVisaCase   VisaCase? @relation(fields: [relatedVisaCaseId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  participants ConversationParticipant[]
  messages     Message[]

  @@index([clientId])
  @@index([category])
  @@index([relatedBookingId])
  @@index([relatedProposalId])
  @@index([relatedVisaCaseId])
  @@map("conversation")
}

// Links a staff member or client to a Conversation with a capacity in that
// thread (blueprint Sections 10.1, 14.3). Two mutually exclusive identity
// paths, mirroring this schema's established split-attribution pattern
// (StaffAssignment's assignee-vs-target split, ProposalAcceptance's
// portal-vs-external response path):
//
// - Staff path — `staffUserId` (a User whose Role is TRAVEL_CONSULTANT,
//   FINANCE_ACCOUNTING, or VISA_DOCUMENTATION) with a matching non-CLIENT
//   `role` value. `clientProfileId` is null.
// - Client path — `clientProfileId` (the client's durable portal identity,
//   matching ProposalAcceptance.respondingClientProfileId's precedent
//   rather than a raw Client FK, since only an activated portal account
//   can actually participate) with `role = CLIENT`. `staffUserId` is null.
//
// Neither FK is schema-restricted to its expected Role/identity — a
// foreign key can't constrain another table's column value, the same
// limitation already documented on StaffAssignment.assignedStaffId above.
// The future conversation-management service must verify `staffUserId`
// actually resolves to a User with a matching non-CLIENT role before
// writing this row, the same way StaffAssignment's own doc comment defers
// an equivalent check.
//
// `joinedAt`/`removedAt` preserve membership history rather than deleting
// a row when a participant (typically an optional Finance or Visa
// Documentation participant, Section 10.1) is removed — matching
// StaffAssignment's `endedAt` convention
// (.claude/rules/admin-dashboard.md's Destructive and Irreversible
// Actions). A participant may later rejoin the same Conversation; the
// partial unique indexes below deliberately scope on `removedAt IS NULL`
// so a new active row can be added after an old one is marked removed,
// without deleting or reusing the removed row.
//
// `lastReadAt` is per-participant read-state storage only (D-016's MVP
// read model, blueprint Section 10.1's "read status") — see the Message
// model doc comment below for exactly how it is interpreted. Storing a
// read timestamp here does **not** itself grant, extend, or verify
// access: the future service layer must always run its own authorization
// check before ever reading or writing this field, never infer
// authorization from the mere presence of a ConversationParticipant row
// or a non-null `lastReadAt`.
//
// Prisma's schema language cannot express a conditional cross-column
// constraint tying `role` to which identity column is populated — migration
// `20260717010520_conversation_schema_constraints` adds this raw SQL by
// hand. This single constraint both enforces the staff/client role-identity
// match AND, as a direct consequence of its two mutually exclusive
// branches, guarantees exactly one of `staffUserId`/`clientProfileId` is
// non-null (a separate `num_nonnulls` constraint would be redundant with
// it):
//   ALTER TABLE "conversation_participant" ADD CONSTRAINT
//     "conversation_participant_identity_role_match"
//     CHECK (
//       ("role" = 'CLIENT' AND "clientProfileId" IS NOT NULL AND "staffUserId" IS NULL)
//       OR
//       ("role" != 'CLIENT' AND "staffUserId" IS NOT NULL AND "clientProfileId" IS NULL)
//     );
//
// This schema also cannot express a partial unique index preventing a
// duplicate *active* membership row for the same person in the same
// Conversation while still allowing historical removed rows and later
// rejoining — the same constraints migration adds these two by hand,
// mirroring StaffAssignment's active-assignment partial-unique-index
// precedent:
//   CREATE UNIQUE INDEX "conversation_participant_active_staff_key"
//     ON "conversation_participant" ("conversationId", "staffUserId")
//     WHERE "removedAt" IS NULL AND "staffUserId" IS NOT NULL;
//   CREATE UNIQUE INDEX "conversation_participant_active_client_profile_key"
//     ON "conversation_participant" ("conversationId", "clientProfileId")
//     WHERE "removedAt" IS NULL AND "clientProfileId" IS NOT NULL;
model ConversationParticipant {
  id String @id

  conversationId String
  conversation   Conversation @relation(fields: [conversationId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  role ConversationParticipantRole

  staffUserId String?
  staffUser   User?   @relation(fields: [staffUserId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  clientProfileId String?
  clientProfile   ClientProfile? @relation(fields: [clientProfileId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  joinedAt  DateTime  @default(now())
  removedAt DateTime?

  lastReadAt DateTime?

  @@index([conversationId, removedAt])
  @@index([staffUserId, removedAt])
  @@index([clientProfileId, removedAt])
  @@map("conversation_participant")
}

// An individual entry within a Conversation (blueprint Sections 10.1,
// 14.3), including its client-visible/internal-note status
// (`MessageVisibility`, above). Two mutually exclusive author paths,
// mirroring ConversationParticipant's identity split immediately above:
//
// - Staff path — `authorStaffUserId`. `authorClientProfileId` is null.
// - Client path — `authorClientProfileId` (the client's durable portal
//   identity, matching ConversationParticipant's own client path).
//   `authorStaffUserId` is null.
//
// Whether an author must hold an active ConversationParticipant row at the
// moment they post is NOT resolved by this schema — it depends on the
// same still-open, role-specific authorization policy the file header's
// authorization-deferral note describes: a CLIENT author's authorization
// requires both ownership of the Conversation's Client (via ClientProfile)
// and active participation; FINANCE_ACCOUNTING and VISA_DOCUMENTATION
// authors require explicit active participation, since neither has an
// assignment-based path onto a Conversation; a TRAVEL_CONSULTANT author's
// authorization turns on active Client/Booking assignment, with whether an
// explicit participant row is additionally required left open; and an
// ADMIN_MANAGER author may be authorized by role alone, without any
// participant row, if the future enforcement decision permits posting
// without participant membership. `authorStaffUserId`/
// `authorClientProfileId` alone — the mere presence of a value in either
// column — must never be treated as proof of authorization; they only
// record who wrote the message, never that they were allowed to. The
// future messaging service must verify authorization to post according to
// whichever final policy is adopted, transactionally, before writing a
// Message; this checkpoint does not resolve that policy.
//
// This checkpoint does add one database-level content restriction: a
// client-authored message can never be INTERNAL_NOTE — internal staff
// notes are by definition not something a client writes (Section 10.1: a
// message is either client-visible or an internal-only note; clients only
// ever produce client-visible ones). Prisma's schema language cannot
// express a conditional cross-column constraint tying `visibility` to
// which author column is populated, so migration
// `20260717010520_conversation_schema_constraints` adds this raw SQL by
// hand, alongside the author-path exclusivity check:
//   ALTER TABLE "message" ADD CONSTRAINT "message_author_path_exclusive"
//     CHECK (num_nonnulls("authorStaffUserId", "authorClientProfileId") = 1);
//   ALTER TABLE "message" ADD CONSTRAINT
//     "message_client_author_not_internal_note"
//     CHECK ("authorClientProfileId" IS NULL OR "visibility" != 'INTERNAL_NOTE');
//
// Read state (blueprint Section 10.1's "read status") is deliberately NOT
// a field on this model — a Conversation may have more than two
// participants (Section 10.1), so a single shared boolean cannot
// correctly represent "read" for every participant at once. Per D-016's
// MVP read model, read state is instead per-participant: a Message is
// considered read for a given ConversationParticipant when this row's
// `createdAt` is at or before that participant's
// `ConversationParticipant.lastReadAt` (see that model's doc comment
// above). The future service layer owns updating `lastReadAt` and
// resolving any timestamp/ordering edge cases (e.g. a message inserted
// with a `createdAt` earlier than an already-recorded `lastReadAt`, or two
// messages sharing an identical `createdAt`); this schema only stores the
// raw values.
//
// No edit/delete flag or read booleans exist here — the blueprint does
// not describe message editing or deletion (Section 10.1 lists only
// "timestamps and read status"), so none is modeled.
model Message {
  id String @id

  conversationId String
  conversation   Conversation @relation(fields: [conversationId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  body       String
  visibility MessageVisibility

  authorStaffUserId String?
  authorStaffUser   User?   @relation(fields: [authorStaffUserId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  authorClientProfileId String?
  authorClientProfile   ClientProfile? @relation(fields: [authorClientProfileId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())

  attachments MessageAttachment[]

  // Deterministic conversation-ordering: (conversationId, createdAt, id) —
  // `id` as the final tiebreaker so two messages sharing an identical
  // `createdAt` still sort deterministically, since `id` is never reused
  // (.claude/rules/database-security.md's Identifiers and Timestamps).
  @@index([conversationId, createdAt, id])
  @@index([authorStaffUserId])
  @@index([authorClientProfileId])
  @@map("message")
}

// A file attached to a Message (blueprint Sections 10.1, 14.3). Minimal
// secure metadata only, consistent with this project's backend-mediated
// storage boundary (`.claude/rules/architecture.md`'s Storage boundary:
// "access mediated by the backend (never direct public bucket URLs for
// sensitive files)") and Section 12.3's signed/expiring-link requirement
// for sensitive files generally.
//
// `storageKey` is an opaque, backend-resolved identifier for the
// underlying stored object — never a public or directly browsable URL.
// `@unique` so the same storage object can never be attached to two
// MessageAttachment rows, mirroring PortalInvitation.tokenHash's
// uniqueness rationale (a value that must resolve to exactly one owning
// record). Actual signed/expiring URL issuance, malware scanning, and
// file-type/size validation at upload time are future service-layer
// concerns (Section 12.3; .claude/rules/database-security.md's Safe file
// handling for uploads) — not enforced or modeled by this schema beyond
// storing `mimeType`/`fileSizeBytes` for that future validation to read
// and act on.
//
// `onDelete: Restrict` on `message`: never drop a Message out from under
// an attachment that documents it, matching this schema's established
// convention.
model MessageAttachment {
  id String @id

  messageId String
  message   Message @relation(fields: [messageId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  storageKey    String @unique
  fileName      String
  mimeType      String
  fileSizeBytes Int

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())

  @@index([messageId])
  @@map("message_attachment")
}

// --- Visa Case Schema Foundation: schema-and-migration checkpoint ---
// Adds VisaCaseStatus, VisaCase, and VisaStatusHistory, and extends
// StaffAssignment and Conversation (see their model doc comments above)
// so VisaCase is a supported assignment target and Conversation
// related-record type (blueprint Sections 4.5, 4.7, 5, 5.1, 5.2, 8, 13.8,
// 14.1, 14.8; docs/HERITAGE_V3_DECISIONS_LOG.md D-017).
//
// Stage A first added this schema and D-017 without creating or applying
// any migration. Migration `20260717024618_visa_case_schema_foundation`
// was subsequently generated (a single `prisma migrate dev --create-only`
// invocation — see D-016 for why re-invoking that command is unsafe and
// must not happen a second time), reviewed, hand-augmented with the
// constraints documented on each model below, and applied to local
// `heritage_v3_dev` on July 17, 2026. It has not been applied to staging
// or production. No repository layer, service layer, API route, admin
// dashboard or client portal UI, tests, or seed data exists either. In
// particular, this checkpoint deliberately does NOT implement:
//
// - VisaRequirement, Document, DocumentRequirement, or DocumentReview —
//   VisaRequirement's blueprint description (Section 14.8: "defines what
//   is required for a specific VisaCase (documents, forms, deadlines)")
//   overlaps structurally with DocumentRequirement (Section 14.7: "defines
//   which document categories are required for a given Booking or
//   VisaCase"), and neither Document nor DocumentRequirement exists
//   anywhere in this schema yet. Modeling VisaRequirement now risks a
//   shape that would need reworking once those entities land, so it is
//   deferred entirely rather than guessed at.
// - Any applicant/traveler, passport, nationality, embassy, or other
//   identity-document field, and any notes or arbitrary JSON field —
//   VisaCase in this checkpoint is a workflow/status shell only. Blueprint
//   Section 13.8 gives no VisaCase field list (unlike Client Section 13.3
//   or Booking Section 13.4), so none is invented; the data-minimization
//   principle in `.claude/rules/database-security.md` and blueprint
//   Section 9.1's caution against storing identity documents or unrelated
//   personal information outside their proper, dedicated model both apply
//   with particular force to visa data specifically.
// - A VisaCase status-transition matrix — the nine `VisaCaseStatus` values
//   (D-017) name states only; no transition graph is modeled or implied by
//   their declaration order. Enforcement is deferred to a later service/API
//   checkpoint, the same way `BookingStatus`'s transition matrix was
//   deferred to its own later, separate D-014 checkpoint.
// - `features/assignments`' `TargetKind` union, service, audit, and
//   authorization code — see the StaffAssignment model doc comment above.
// - VisaCase/VisaStatusHistory repository and service layers, API routes,
//   UI, VisaCase-authorization rules (who may create or change a VisaCase;
//   how VisaCase-level and Booking-level StaffAssignment interact — both
//   left open by D-017, not assumed here), notifications, and tests/seed
//   data.

// A full, self-defined enum — unlike every earlier status enum in this
// file (LeadStatus, BookingStatus, PortalInvitationStatus), which were
// each adopted directly from an explicit blueprint-given list, blueprint
// Section 13.8 states outright that "the detailed visa status list will be
// finalized alongside implementation planning," and Section 16.2
// separately lists it as an open decision. D-017 resolves it. `APPROVED`,
// `REJECTED`, and `WITHDRAWN` are terminal (D-017) — nothing in this
// schema enforces that terminality yet; a future transition-enforcement
// checkpoint owns that rule, the same way `BookingStatus`'s terminal
// states (`COMPLETED`, `CANCELLED`) are enforced only by D-014's
// service-layer transition matrix, never by the enum declaration itself.
enum VisaCaseStatus {
  OPENED
  REQUIREMENTS_PENDING
  UNDER_REVIEW
  ADDITIONAL_INFORMATION_REQUIRED
  READY_FOR_SUBMISSION
  SUBMITTED
  APPROVED
  REJECTED
  WITHDRAWN
}

// The conditional visa workflow record for a Booking (blueprint Sections
// 5, 8, 13.8, 14.8), created only when visa assistance is actually
// required — never automatically for every Booking (Section 5.1's
// non-automatic creation rule; Section 8: "A visa case is only created
// when the client or destination actually requires visa assistance").
//
// Per D-017, this checkpoint models exactly **zero or one** VisaCase per
// Booking for the MVP — not multiple historical or simultaneous
// VisaCases, and not traveler-level VisaCase modeling (e.g. one case per
// traveler on a multi-traveler Booking), both explicitly out of scope.
// `bookingId` is `@unique` to enforce this at the database level: a second
// `POST`-equivalent attempt against the same Booking would violate this
// constraint rather than silently succeed. This is deliberately a plain
// `@unique`, not a partial unique index — unlike
// `ProposalVersion`'s "at most one *current* version" or
// `StaffAssignment`'s "at most one *active* assignment" patterns, there is
// no historical/superseded VisaCase concept in this checkpoint for a
// partial index to distinguish; the constraint is simply "at most one,
// ever, per Booking."
//
// `clientId` is a direct FK, mirroring this schema's established
// Lead.clientId/Proposal.clientId/Booking.clientId/Conversation.clientId
// convention, rather than something derivable only by walking
// `booking.clientId`. Service-layer invariant for later implementation,
// not enforced by any database constraint in this checkpoint (the
// database cannot verify a fact that depends on the state of another row,
// matching this schema's established precedent for Booking.clientId vs.
// its ProposalVersion's Proposal.clientId): **`VisaCase.clientId` must
// always equal the Client connected through `VisaCase.booking.clientId`.**
// The future VisaCase-creation service must verify this transactionally
// at write time — skipping it risks a cross-client data leak, which
// `.claude/rules/client-portal.md` treats as critical severity. This
// schema does not, and cannot, attempt to solve this with duplicated or
// derived-column logic; do not add one.
//
// `status` defaults to `OPENED`. Who may create a VisaCase, and who beyond
// Visa Documentation Staff (blueprint Section 4.5) may change its status —
// including whether Admin/Manager's Section 4.2 "full visibility" extends
// to edit capability here, which is not explicitly granted the way other
// roles' "manage X" capabilities are — is left an open decision (D-017),
// not assumed by this schema.
//
// `onDelete: Restrict` on both `client` and `booking`: neither can be
// removed out from under a VisaCase that documents its own workflow
// history, matching this schema's established convention.
model VisaCase {
  id String @id

  clientId String
  client   Client @relation(fields: [clientId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  bookingId String  @unique
  booking   Booking @relation(fields: [bookingId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  status VisaCaseStatus @default(OPENED)

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt

  statusHistory    VisaStatusHistory[]
  staffAssignments StaffAssignment[]

  // The Conversation Schema Foundation's related-record model, extended by
  // this checkpoint — see the Conversation model doc comment above.
  conversations Conversation[]

  @@index([clientId])
  @@index([status])
  @@map("visa_case")
}

// Timestamped record of every VisaCase status change (blueprint Sections
// 13.8, 14.8; .claude/rules/database-security.md Identifiers and
// Timestamps; .claude/rules/backend.md Auditability), mirroring
// BookingStatusHistory's convention exactly. Append-only in practice: the
// repository layer built in a later checkpoint must only ever INSERT here.
//
// `changedByUserId` is required (D-017), not nullable — matching
// `BookingStatusHistory.changedByUserId` rather than
// `LeadStatusHistory.changedByUserId` (nullable there because a lead's
// initial NEW status may originate from an unauthenticated public
// submission with no staff actor). This is D-017's own MVP policy, not a
// requirement blueprint Section 5.1 itself imposes: Section 5.1
// establishes only that a VisaCase is created deliberately, by an
// explicit staff *or system* action, never automatically as a side
// effect — it does not say every creation must be staff-attributed. Per
// D-017, this MVP schema requires an attributable staff User on every
// row, including the initial one; a future automated/actorless status
// change would need a superseding decision and a schema change (making
// this column nullable again) before it could be modeled.
//
// `previousStatus` is nullable for the same reason as
// `BookingStatusHistory`'s: a VisaCase's first history row (its initial
// `OPENED` status) has no prior status to record.
//
// Migration `20260717024618_visa_case_schema_foundation` added one CHECK
// constraint Prisma cannot express, mirroring
// `booking_status_history_status_changed` in spirit (though using `<>`
// rather than that constraint's `!=` — both are equivalent PostgreSQL
// inequality operators; this one simply matches the exact text reviewed
// and approved for this constraint):
//   ALTER TABLE "visa_status_history"
//   ADD CONSTRAINT "visa_status_history_status_changed"
//   CHECK ("previousStatus" IS NULL OR "previousStatus" <> "newStatus");
// This constraint is applied and validated on local `heritage_v3_dev`; see
// the file-header note above this section for staging/production status.
model VisaStatusHistory {
  id String @id

  visaCaseId String
  visaCase   VisaCase @relation(fields: [visaCaseId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  previousStatus VisaCaseStatus?
  newStatus      VisaCaseStatus

  // `onDelete: Restrict`: never drop the acting staff member's identity off
  // an existing history row, matching this schema's established
  // convention (LeadStatusHistory.changedByUserId, AuditLog.actorId,
  // BookingStatusHistory.changedByUserId). See the model doc comment above
  // for why this is required, not nullable.
  changedByUserId String
  changedBy       User   @relation("VisaStatusHistoryActor", fields: [changedByUserId], references: [id], onDelete: Restrict)

  createdAt DateTime @default(now())

  @@index([visaCaseId, createdAt])
  @@index([changedByUserId])
  @@index([createdAt])
  @@map("visa_status_history")
}
